ath family, Ericaceae. It is native to North America and is commonly known as kinnikinnick or bearberry. The plant is an evergreen shrub that typically grows up to 2 feet in height and produces small, white or pink flowers in the spring. Uva-ursi polifolia is also known for its red, waxy berries that are eaten by birds and small mammals. The plant's berries and leaves have been used in traditional medicine for their antimicrobial properties.", "benefits": "Uva-ursi polifolia, also known as Bearberry, has been traditionally used in herbal medicine for its potential health benefits. The plant's leaves are rich in arbutin, a compound that has been shown to have antimicrobial and anti-inflammatory properties. As a result, Uva-ursi polifolia is often used to treat urinary tract infections and to help soothe conditions such as cystitis and urethritis. Additionally, the plant's antioxidant properties may help to protect against cell damage and reduce the risk of certain diseases. However, further research is needed to fully understand the extent of Uva-ursi polifolia's health benefits and potential interactions with other medications.", "parts": "Uva-ursi polifolia, also known as bearberry, is a shrub native to Northern Europe and North America. The medicinal parts of Uva-ursi polifolia are primarily its leaves and fruits, which have been used in traditional medicine for centuries. The leaves of the plant contain arbutin, a compound that has antimicrobial and anti-inflammatory properties. Uva-ursi polifolia has been used to treat urinary tract infections, digestive issues, and skin conditions. The plant's leaves and fruits can be consumed as a tea or used topically in the form of salves or creams."}